Hardware Wiring (Arduino ↔ PCA9685 ↔ Inputs)
1. I²C (Arduino ↔ PCA9685)

The PCA9685 is controlled over I²C.

Arduino Pin	PCA9685 Pin	Purpose
A4	SDA	I²C data
A5	SCL	I²C clock
GND	GND	Common ground

⚠️ Arduino ground must be shared with the PCA9685 and joystick ground.

2. Servo Connections (PCA9685)

Servos plug only into the PCA9685, not the Arduino.

Servo Index (Code)	PCA9685 Channel
Servo 0	Channel 0
Servo 1	Channel 1
Servo 2	Channel 2
Servo 3	Channel 3
Servo 4	Channel 4
Servo 5	Channel 5
Servo 6	Channel 6
Servo 7 (gripper)	Channel 7

Signal wire → PCA9685 signal pin

Power wire → PCA9685 V+ (external 5–6.6 V supply)

Ground wire → PCA9685 GND

3. External Servo Power (Required)

Servos must NOT be powered from the Arduino.

External PSU	PCA9685
+5–6.6 V	V+
GND	GND

Also connect PSU GND → Arduino GND (common ground).

4. Joystick Wiring (2× Analog Joysticks)

Each joystick has VRx, VRy, VCC, GND.

Joystick 1
Arduino Pin	Function
A0	J1_X
A1	J1_Y
5V	VCC
GND	GND
Joystick 2
Arduino Pin	Function
A2	J2_X
A3	J2_Y
5V	VCC
GND	GND
5. Button (Gripper Control)
Arduino Pin	Connection
D3	Button leg 1
GND	Button leg 2

Button uses INPUT_PULLUP

Pressed = LOW

No external resistor required

6. Important Notes

PCA9685 OE pin should be left unconnected or tied to GND

Red LED on PCA9685 indicates logic power (normal)

Servo movement depends entirely on external V+ power

On startup, all servos center to 1500 µs (90°) one by one

Pin Summary (Quick Copy)
Arduino A4 → PCA SDA
Arduino A5 → PCA SCL
Arduino GND → PCA GND → PSU GND

Joystick 1: A0, A1
Joystick 2: A2, A3

Button: D3 → GND

Servos: PCA channels 0–7
